            <span id="Second_Paragraph_Mod">
                 
                Anton Layes Sr. was born in Germany, and had two sons, Anton Jr. and Jacob Frank, by his first wife. I do not know her name, but Jacob’s daughter Mary Frances said she was French. She died, and Anton married Katarina Rott, who was much younger than him, and also from Germany. They had five children and then moved to Stanton County Nebraska, and had another child, then went to an unknown place, then to Brown, Arkansas, then to Scranton, where they had my grandfather John and another son. Everyone thought Scranton would be a big coal mine but it didn't work. It had been named after Scranton, Pennsylvania, a coal mining town. Anton Jr. had stayed in Germany and served in the army. Jacob moved to Idaho. <br /><br />

                The Besselman family went from Germany to St. Clair County (also Roosevelt), Morrisons Bluff, and Brown/Scranton. The whole group of the Besselmans were in St. Louis for seven to eight months, then moved to Arkansas. Henry and Elizabeth (known as Lizzie or Lisette Tieman or Teeman) settled in Shoal Creek. Henry had two sisters. Mary Elizabeth married Conrad Elskin and Anna married Fred Bunker. Anna and Fred had a baby who died and is buried in Shoal Creek. 
 
            </span>
            
            <span id="See_More_Mod"><a href="#" id="restofstory0-show"  onclick="showHide('restofstory0');return false;">SEE MORE</a>
            </span>

            <div id="restofstory0" class="more">

                <span id="Second_Paragraph_Mod1" class="more">

                    The Anton Layes and Henry Bessleman families lived down the road from each other in Paris. They each had eight to nine children. Henry Besselman had a vineyard and made wine. Three of the Layes brothers Charles, John and Joe married three of the Besselman sisters Mary, Clara and Bertha. An older Besselman sister Anna had 14 children. Three babies, Joseph and Peter (twins) and Francis died of unknown causes and 15-year-old Elizabeth Lily died of appendicitis.<br /><br />

                    My grandpa and grandma (John Layes and Clara Besselman) moved to Scranton and had three children. Helena was born in 1909, but died before the 1910 census. My dad, John Boniface was born in 1914. Emma was born in 1918 but died as a young baby of diarrhea. They don’t know what caused it, but Dad remembered it was after eating a blackberry. Grandpa Layes owned rental homes and the cotton gin and flour mill in Scranton.<br /><br />

                    Surnames on my mother’s side are Beshoner, Nehus, Bergholt, and Nietsche. The Bergholt direct line and the Nehus came from Germany to Freeport, Illinois then to Paris, Arkansas. Other Bergholts scattered to Wisconsin and other Midwest states.<br /><br />

                    My great-grandpa and grandma were Frank Beshoner and Pauline Nietsche. They came to Shoal Creek from Germany via New Orleans in 1879. They had all their possessions in one trunk. That trunk is in Oklahoma, now owned by Sandy Culp Bailey, a descendant of their first child, Bertha Beshoner Bartsch. I have never found them on a passenger list, but I keep searching. They had eleven children. My grandfather Joseph was their sixth child, born 1887. Frank died about 1894, before the last child was born.<br /><br />

                    Abel Nehus came to Freeport from Germany when he was 14. He married Wilhelmenia Bergholte in Freeport on May 27, 1880. Juliafrank was their fifth of seven children. <br /><br />

                    Joseph Beshoner married Julia Nehus on September 11, 1912. My mother Estelle was their oldest child of five. <br /><br />

                    My father John Jr. married Estelle Beshoner on February 12, 1935. Everyone called her “Stella.” They had first met in Paris when they were in 8th grade at a Catholic confirmation which was held in a central place for the people in the area. Estelle was 2 years older than John Jr. They bought one of John Sr.’s rental homes and lived there for 20 years, then built a house up on the farm on the hill in 1955. My parents didn't really want to live in a house right by his parents, but it was a nice house. It was a two-story with a full high-ceiling basement. It only had one bathroom, but that was before most people had indoor bathrooms. There was an empty lot between the homes, which provided some separation, but my Grandpa Layes still expected my dad to help around his place.<br /><br />

                    I was born October 22, 1936. Clarine was born in July of 1939, John was born in March of 1942, Ron was born in February of 1943, and Charlie was born in October of 1955, when they were building the house up on the hill. My dad had saved money to build the house on the hill and my grandpa didn't want him to build up there because it was the wheat field. They also grew cotton and raised cattle. They had a cotton gin, saw mill, wheat mill and ice plant. They advertised their ice in the Paris newspaper. John Sr. and Clara had a grocery store in their basement. They had a large dining room table down in the basement and another one upstairs in the dining room. My grandma had a cot in the dining room where my grandma would take a nap, probably because it was cooler there. The ceiling in the basement area had crown molding and was covered with decorative tin tiles, which were in style then. We had a lot of dinners on the one downstairs. I don’t remember the upstairs table ever being used. There was a coal room with an outside chute next to the kitchen. My grandpa Layes had a gun in the safe and a wine room by the office. <br /><br />

                    My Grandpa’s brother, Frank farmed and was a blacksmith, and telephone operator. It was in his house—he would connect the numbers together. He was sick for awhile and died in 1930. My grandpa would hire Frank’s boys to work at the cotton gin, saw, mill flour, and farm. In depression times he paid them to pick up rocks around the properties, mostly so they would have some work to do and some money. My dad delivered ice when he was a teenager and young man. Grandpa paid us grandkids to pick weeds out of the cotton. He usually paid us the same as the workers, which did not make my mom happy. She didn’t think we should get so much. After the war, the nephews scattered elsewhere in the country for jobs.

                </span>
            </div>
