            <span id="Second_Paragraph_Mod">
                I lived in the Scranton house my whole life until my senior year. The house was very nice. The well was outside and they pumped the water in the house. Then they got it plumbed and got improved electricity etc. There was party line phones. We had a basketball hoop and a tennis court made of packed and rolled dirt with a high fence. The neighborhood kids liked to come over to play. Dad was going to put in a swimming pool but never did. Many years later he put in a hot tub at the house on the hill. He also dug for a swimming pool but the tornado hit good Friday 1974 and he never completed the pool. He filled the hole with debris and covered it up.<br /><br />

                In the front of the house was a porch and the living room and a bedroom. Then there was the dining room and kitchen in the back. A bath was on the left of the kitchen and an enclosed porch with windows was on the right. The back porch had a laundry area with a ringing washer and a built-in toybox. We had to clean out the toy box when we got new toys. In the kitchen, by the porch was an enclosed stairway. Under the stairs was storage for food. There was not a basement. We had four large bedrooms upstairs with double beds. Clarine and I shared a room. There were storage closets with moth balls, etc. and we would rotate out the clothes with the seasons. The house had to be perfect and the yard too, with no toys laying around. 
            </span>

            <span id="See_More_Mod"><a href="#" id="restofstory-show"  onclick="showHide('restofstory');return false;">SEE MORE</a>
            </span>

            <div id="restofstory" class="more">

                <span id="Second_Paragraph_Mod1" class="more">
                    A little girl named Dolvory lived with her grandparents (Ross) across the road from us. Dolvory got her name from combining the soap names Oxydol and Ivory. She eventually got married and bought our house from whoever bought it from us after we moved up the hill. There was a driveway on the right side of the house and a train depot in the back to the right. It was no longer operating. There was a big garden to the right also. Everything was dirt roads back then.<br /><br />

                    Behind the house was the railroad tracks but they were not in use. One day Dolvory and Bill Wayne “Champ” Georgia, Bill Ross (who lived across the street) and Frankie Gerard stole a pump car and rode it off the tracks into the creek. “Good Rainwater,” a man who lived and worked in the depot rescued them and didn't tell their parents. Later those kids moved to California and their mother was hit by a car and killed. The kids saw everything—her guts, etc. <br /><br />

                    My dad didn’t want pets, so we played with the wild cats by the mill. We had a cat once that was cute and he liked it. Then one day while we were visiting Grandma Beshoner in Paris, it got hit by a car and died. Dad worried about how I would be. <br /><br />

                    Part of my chores was to listen to the boys reading after school. Ron was more studious and a better student than John. Clarine and I did laundry, made beds, did dishes, and cleaned the bathrooms. We would switch off jobs, like one week I would wash the dark clothes and the Clarine would wash the whites, and I would wash the dishes and Clarine would dry. Then the next week we would switch. We made cookies, cakes, fried chicken, fried potatoes and even though Clarine was younger than me, we had the same responsibilities. She tried to keep up with me. She couldn't crochet as well though, because she was left-handed. We didn’t take extra music lessons or anything like that. One year Dad bought an old building and John and Ron had to chip concrete off the bricks. They also worked in the garden. They fed the corn stocks to the cows but didn't harvest the ears of corn. <br /><br />

                    My mom was a good seamstress and made most of our clothes. She wore her trimming scissors on a cord around her neck. Later in life Dad would grumble when Mom went to baby showers. He said they had to get all their own kids’ clothes, everyone else should too. She made fried pork rinds every now and then. I guess they weren’t that good for us, but they tasted great. We raised pigs and had a smoke house with ham, ribs, and sausages. They also canned bacon and sausages. It was not easy to pull it out of the jar, and I am not really fond of bacon because of that.<br /><br />

                    Rosie, my mom’s youngest sister was in the convent in Ft. Smith. We would visit Beshoner cousins in Paris. My cousin Demp snuck wine and Clarine and Teresa joined in. Another time John and Ron got some, but they were acting too goofy and the adults found out. There is a huge magnolia tree growing by the Beshoner home in Paris. My mom’s Grandpa Beshoner planted the seed to the tree.<br /><br />

                    There was an old fashioned general store in Scranton. It seemed normal to me, but it was different than the stores in Ft. Smith. We went to Erma’s beauty shop for perms, etc.<br /><br />

                    I got appendicitis when I was 12 and stayed in the Paris Hospital, but I did not have to have it surgically removed. My parents had an insurance plan for the hospital. It cost a dollar for the plan. My grandpa Layes had his appendix out. My dad was scared because my grandma Clara’s niece Elizabeth Lily had died of appendicitis, and Bertha and Joe Bessleman’s daughter Leona May Layes had died of anesthesia allergy during appendix surgery when she was 21. <br /><br />

                    My grandpa Joe Beshoner broke his leg once while coupling the train for the mine. He got caught between them. He was in the Paris hospital for that also. August Bartch supplied electricity for the hospital.<br /><br />

                    My dad got tickets to the Rodeo from Bruce Rogers Plumbing Supplies (they gave them out for Christmas to their customers) We used to get to go to the rodeo and sit in box seats every year. We saw the cowboys get bucked off the bulls and I liked the clowns. He got other little gifts from Fort Smith Cotton and Oil company. 
