            <span id="Second_Paragraph_Mod">
                
                I moved up to Missouri the next school year for second grade. We lived at 315 Accidental Court. I don’t have any memory of my second-grade teacher there. I attended St. Mary’s school. On Sunday afternoons, we would drive in the county. My cousin Ricky was born with Down syndrome. Lawrence was still gone. My grandmother Beshoner worried it was paint that caused it because Francis had done some painting. (Many years later, Down syndrome was identified as a chromosome 21 trisomy by Dr. Jérôme Lejeune in 1959.)<br /><br />

                In 1944 Jerome, my mom’s brother, was reported as killed when his plane went down. He was a tail gunner in a fighter plane. While we were in Independence, our neighbors the Borgedines—Betty and Stella and their mother, moved into house while we were gone. They later moved to Ft. Smith and then to California.

                
            </span>

            <!--span id="See_More_Mod"><a href="#" id="restofstoryb-show"  onclick="showHide('restofstoryb');return false;">SEE MORE</a>
