            <span id="Second_Paragraph_Mod">    

                One day, they were probably about twelve or so, they decided they wanted to see if they could get some cotton to burn. So they picked a cotton bale. One of them got brave—I don’t know how they chose who was going to go inside my grandmother’s (Clara Layes’) house to ask for a match, but one of them went and said, “Dad needs a match right now!” And my grandmother gave him a match. And then they went out to the lot where the cotton bales were, and they started burning the cotton bale. It was hard to start, I’m sure, but they burned the whole cotton bale. For some people, that was a whole year’s wages. Because they grew the cotton, they chopped the cotton, they picked the cotton, they hauled it to the cotton gin to be ginned, and they sold the bale. But since they burned it, they didn’t have a bale of cotton to sell.   <br /><br />

                Sometimes the cotton would catch on fire by other means. The bales were huge and weighed 1,000 pounds. The cotton was put in a bale box and bound with metal bands. Then they were labeled with red metal tags according to the various grades of cotton. Each grade got a different price. Some were for seed, some for fertilizer, etc. They were rolled up a ramp onto the trucks to the buyer. We sold bales to one place, and seeds to another to be used for oil, etc. 
 
