                <span id="Second_Paragraph_Mod1" class="more">
                    When it was time to bring the cotton to the market, my mom weighed trucks at the cotton gin. When she worked, Clarine and I had to get the clothes off the line and make potato salad with mayonnaise or German potato salad with vinegar because Dad liked it better. We also had to listen for the cotton buyers calling with price quotes. The prices were top secret and we had a private line phone to handle the calls. When we got a call we had to run to the gin to tell my dad they were on the phone with the price. The mill was very loud, and it was hard to get them to notice and hear us. I didn’t like listening for the calls because I wanted to play, and sometimes I would try not to hear the phone.   <br /><br />

                    When Ron and John went to high school, they went to St. Benedict’s Academy, and we lived in Scranton and the academy was in Subiaco, so they had to ride a bus there. And they were the bus drivers, so they drove the bus. One day while they were going up the hill to our house, which was a curvy road, they went off the road, probably going faster than they should have been going up at that hill on those curves. They wrecked the school bus and that had to be repaired. My dad was really not happy with them, so he had a notice put into the paper, that he was no longer responsible for the actions of his two sons, that they were responsible for their own actions, that he was not responsible anymore, and he would not put up with them anymore. 
