            <span id="Second_Paragraph_Mod">
                The lights were eight to a string on a fabric cord. Sometimes they were shaped like lanterns or Santa or snowmen. The fireplace mantel had greenery and the windows had a lighted wreath in them. We did not hang up stockings. We got gifts from Santa and when we got older, we exchanged them. After Christmas Eve Mass we would get to open one gift. <br /><br />
                
                For Easter, we got shoeboxes and went outside and picked grass and flowers and put them in our shoeboxes. Then we would leave the boxes out at night. My parents would color eggs and put them in the boxes during the night. We had egg hunts if it wasn’t rainy. We had a normal Sunday dinner. We probably had ham as there was always some in the smoke house. Every Monday after Easter, we had a big egg hunt at school. I don’t know who got all those eggs ready and hid them. It just happened, I never thought about that. During Lent, which lasted four weeks, we went through the Stations of the Cross. On Ash Wednesday, the priest would put ashes on our foreheads symbolically and say “Ashes to ashes, dust to dust.” Each week we gave up something. I usually gave up candy because it was hard to give up, but I didn’t get it very often anyway.  


            </span>


