                    Fourth of July was a big deal. It was my grandpa Layes’ birthday. He used to have a huge celebration with a live community brass band, flags set up across the front porch, firecrackers, and Roman candles. His nieces would come help cook a big chicken dinner with hot potato salad made with vinegar, or mashed potatoes. As he got older, when I was born, the celebrations were not quite as huge. I remember there was always a big tub of homemade ice cream and a big tub of pop bottles in ice. He always had a three-layer cake of strawberry, vanilla, and chocolate. It had seven-minute frosting that my mom made. He used to have Grandma Layes’ frosting but it was buttercream, and Grandpa liked my mom’s better. <br /><br />
 
                For Memorial Day, we didn’t do a whole lot because we had the Catholic holiday “All Souls Day.” We would decorate all servicemen’s graves. We started back to school after Labor Day and then when the cotton crop was ready, we stayed home to pick cotton and help get the crop in.<br /><br />

                For Halloween we did not go trick or treating. We went to parties at the High School. My mom made up costumes out of big sheets of crepe paper.<br /><br /> 

                    Once, Clarine went with her friends Wanda Jane and “Baby” Ruth to a Halloween party at the high school. When the party was over, they went to the store to get a coke. Grandpa Layes had taken cotton bales up to Ft. Smith. He went to the high school to get them and they weren’t there. He was looking for them everywhere. When they got home, he was not happy because everyone had been worried.<br /><br />

                    For Thanksgiving, we usually had chicken because my dad didn’t like turkey because it was too dry. One year Nuki made a big Thanksgiving dinner for everyone with turkey and my Grandpa Layes had an appendicitis attack so everyone went over to the Paris hospital, and she was there with her big dinner. Everyone came later and ate. We normally had mincemeat and pumpkin pie or applesauce pie. <br /><br />

                    Aside from annual holidays, we went on trips to Missouri to visit my mom’s family. Jodie, Celeste, Hennretta, Rily and Lawrence and younger cousins. When I was about 10 years old we went to the southeastern states. We went to Florida, and swam in the bay in Louisiana. We went to New Orleans, Kentucky, Georgia, Tennessee and Alabama. <br /><br />
                     
                    In 8th grade we went to Waco, Texas to see lumber. Then to New Mexico and to Phoenix where we saw Beshoner, and Schmuki relatives. We went to Hollywood area in California where Mary Nenus and family lived. She was widowed. We saw orange groves and the Hoover Dam, and the petrified forest. We went to Carlsbad Caverns, the Painted Desert, and the Grand Canyon. The boys had football practice in the summer so we couldn’t take a lot of long vacations. We went to places in Arkansas like the hot springs.
