                <span id="Second_Paragraph_Mod1" class="more">
                    When I was a freshman, I lived in a small dorm with four girls. There was two sets of bunk beds, and we rotated beds. My roommates were Charlotte Williams—her uncle Frank Williams was a state representative and was married to Jeanie’s (Ron’s wife) aunt—a Lansing, Martha Netzer who now lives in Henderson NV, Marilou Vonderheide, and Mary Jo Witt from Mina, AK.<br /><br />

                    My sophomore year, we didn’t have bunkbeds. We were in a huge room with curtains around to form our own cubicles. There was one Prefit at each end of the room with us.<br /><br /> 

                    We had our own bed, dresser, and locker to hang our clothes. During the summer the nuns stayed there. Rosie, my aunt, was a nun and was in charge of the gardens after she retired from teaching and she would drive a four-wheeler around to water the grounds. She went to school in Farse, Virginia.<br /><br />

                    There was a large library that the nuns used also. We had art, music, PE, algebra, religion, English, Spanish, and Latin. All the teachers have died now and are buried there. There were band concerts at public schools and we would go see the marching band and other performances in the spring. On Saturdays, we would go shopping or take the bus downtown to a movie etc. Mary Ellen Verfurth took violin private lessons, and I rode the bus with her to lessons. Marta Ann Hendersen married her brother Patrick. The neighbor girl Stella Borgerding who lived by us in Scranton had moved to Ft. Smith, and attended St. Scholastica also. Her grandpa was a pioneer of Arkansas. Seniors went on trips with the Rector to the park for picnics and to the Dairy Queen. There was sour milk there once, and I didn’t like Dairy Queen after that.<br /><br />

                    After high school in 1955, I worked as a typist for Bruce Rogers plumbing and electrical supply. This was where my dad bought his electrical supplies. The office manager was a Sharp. I typed up bills—they were hard to read and I had to know the abbreviations. After that I was a radio station receptionist in Ft. Smith and I also worked at Dixie Cup.<br /><br />
                     
                    I lived in an apartment with Rita Geel from St. Scholastica, and June Kearny, Evelyn Gee, and Mary Ann Buss. There were too many of us so I moved to an apartment with Roberta Hodges from Dixie Cup. We put labels on boxes and typeset the labels and was a secretary. I used shorthand. Our parents expected us to live on our own. Clarine lived in Ft. Smith also in an apartment. Nuki and Demp worked in a bank in Paris. Nuki didn’t get married for a long time. She worked as the doctor’s receptionist and when his wife died, Nuki married him. He was born in 1913 and she was born in 1929 so there was a 15 year difference. He had a little adopted daughter. Demp had Marsha and Steve.
